-> Collection is a container which is used to store group of objects.
-> Collection interface is available in java.util package.
-> List, set, Queue interfaces are extending properties Collections interface.
-> In collections framework we have collections class.

NOTE: Collections is predefined class available in java.lang package

-> Collections class provide several static methods to perform operations in data.

    Ex: Collections.sort();

Q. Wht is the difference between Collection, Collections and collections framework ?

Answer: 

    Defination: Collection is a container to store group of objects.
We have an interface with a name Collection(java.util). It is root interface in Collection framework.

Collections is a class available in java.util package....
(providing redimade methods to perform operations on objects)

Collection interface and Collections class are part of collections framework. Along with these 2 classes there are several
other classes and interfaces in collections framework.


==================================
java program on collections class
==================================

package Collections;

import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.Collections;

public class CollectionsSortingDemo {

	
	public static void main(String[] args) {
		
		ArrayList<Integer> al = new ArrayList<>();
	
		al.add(4);
		al.add(2);
		al.add(1);
		al.add(3);
		
		System.out.println("before sorting :: " + al);
		
		Collections.sort(al);
		
		System.out.println("after sorting :::" + al);
		
		Collections.reverse(al);
		
		System.out.println("in reverse order :::::"+al);
	
	
	}
}



OUTPUT:
========

before sorting :: [4, 2, 1, 3]
after sorting :::[1, 2, 3, 4]
in reverse order :::::[4, 3, 2, 1]




